        <h2>Transportation: Getting Around Europe Cheaply</h2>
        <p>Transportation often represents the largest expense for European backpackers, but numerous budget-friendly options exist. The Eurail Pass can be cost-effective for extensive train travel, especially if you're under 26 and eligible for youth discounts. However, calculate carefully ‚Äì sometimes individual tickets or bus travel proves cheaper.</p>

        <p>Budget airlines like Ryanair, EasyJet, and Wizz Air offer incredibly cheap flights between European cities, sometimes costing less than train tickets. Book early and travel light to avoid baggage fees. FlixBus provides comfortable, affordable bus travel across Europe, perfect for overnight journeys that save on accommodation costs.</p>

        <p>For shorter distances, consider BlaBlaCar for ridesharing opportunities. Many European cities also offer excellent public transportation with day passes that provide unlimited travel within city limits.</p>

        <h2>Accommodation Strategies That Save Money</h2>
        <p>Accommodation costs can quickly spiral out of control, but smart choices keep expenses minimal. Hostels remain the backpacker's best friend, offering beds for $15-40 per night depending on location and season. Book through Hostelworld or Booking.com, and read reviews carefully to ensure quality and safety.</p>

        <p>Consider staying in hostel dormitories rather than private rooms to maximize savings. Many hostels offer kitchen facilities, allowing you to prepare your own meals and save significantly on food costs. Some hostels also provide free breakfast, walking tours, or other perks that add value to your stay.</p>

        <p>Alternative accommodation options include Couchsurfing for free stays with locals, house-sitting opportunities, and work exchanges through platforms like Workaway or WWOOF. These options not only save money but provide authentic cultural experiences and opportunities to meet locals.</p>

